---
title: 05 · streaming decoders
---

Q: What is a streaming decoder, in one definition?
A: A state machine plus retained partial state: `feed(chunk)` consumes as many complete items as the buffered bytes allow, emits them, and keeps the remainder (raw bytes, or digested state like an accumulator). The chunk boundary is transport noise; your job is to make it invisible.

---

Q: The cardinal rule of streaming decoders, and the property test that enforces it.
A: Output must be invariant under every split of the byte stream: `feed(a + b)` produces the same total output as `feed(a); feed(b)` for every split point, including empty chunks. The test: feed the whole stream in one call, byte-at-a-time, and across every 2-part split — all three must yield identical concatenated output. It catches essentially every state-machine bug.

---

Q: Push vs pull APIs for stream decoding.
A: Push: caller hands you bytes (`feed(chunk) -> items`) — composes with event loops (`asyncio.Protocol.data_received`) and is what interviews want. Pull: you call `read(n)` and block — easier straight-line, assumes you own the thread. `asyncio.StreamReader` is pull sugar built on a push core plus backpressure.

---

Q: The two streaming failure modes, precisely.
A: Need more data: the buffered prefix is a valid prefix of some longer valid stream — buffer it, return what you have, never raise. Malformed: no continuation of the buffered bytes can ever be valid — raise `ValueError` immediately; waiting cannot fix it.

---

Q: What does `finish()` / EOF do in a stateful decoder?
A: Closes the loophole: a dangling partial value is "need more data" right up until the stream ends, at which point it becomes malformed (truncated). Every stateful decoder needs an end-of-stream call that raises on dangling state.

---

Q: What happens after a streaming decoder raises?
A: Errors are sticky: the state is undefined; real systems tear down the connection rather than resync. Say so out loud.

---

Q: Resync-after-corruption for the four framing strategies?
A: Length-prefix and TLV: none — desynced forever. Delimiter + escaping: self-heals at the next delimiter. COBS: self-heals at the next `0x00`.

---

Q: Overhead of delimiter-escaping vs COBS?
A: Escaping: worst case 2x expansion (all-delimiter payload) — unacceptable against an MTU budget. COBS: exactly $\lceil n/254 \rceil$ bytes ($\approx 0.4\%$), plus the `0x00` delimiter.

---

Q: The length-prefix DoS, and where the guard belongs.
A: A peer sends 5 bytes claiming a 1 GiB frame; a naive decoder buffers forever. Check `length > max_frame` the moment the length is decoded — before allocating or buffering, not when the payload arrives. The streaming analogue of a bounds check.

---

Q: The COBS encoding rule.
A: Split the data at zeros; emit each zero-free run as code-then-run where `code = len(run) + 1` (1..0xFE); the zero itself is implied by the block boundary.

---

C: A COBS code byte of [0xFF] announces 254 data bytes with [no implied zero] at the block boundary.

---

Q: COBS-encode `11 22 00 33`. Empty input? A single `00`?
A: `03 11 22 02 33` (03 = "2 bytes then a zero", 02 = "1 byte"); empty → `01`; single zero → `01 01`.

---

Q: COBS malformed cases?
A: A zero byte inside encoded data, or a code promising more bytes than remain (truncated).

---

Q: Why does TLV give forward compatibility for free?
A: A reader that doesn't know tag 17 still knows its length, so it skips `length` bytes and keeps parsing — exactly how old protobuf readers survive new fields.

---

Q: Protobuf wire format in one phrase.
A: Varint-key TLV: the key is a varint `(field_number << 3) | wire_type`; wire type 2 (LEN) is varint length + payload, and types 0/1/5 make the length implicit (varint / 8 bytes / 4 bytes).

---

Q: State of a streaming varint decoder?
A: `(accumulator, shift)` — no byte buffer; partial bytes are digested immediately. Per byte: `acc |= (b & 0x7F) << shift`; continuation set → `shift += 7`; else emit `acc` and reset both.

---

Q: The 64-bit bounds inside a streaming varint decoder?
A: At most 10 bytes; at `shift == 63` the byte may contribute only bit 0, so `shift == 63 and b & 0x7E` is overflow, and a continuation bit on the 10th byte is too-long. In Python the bound is policy you must write (ints never overflow); in C it's memory safety — the cast `(uint64_t)(b & 0x7F)` is mandatory and `shift >= 64` is UB.

---

Q: UTF-8 streaming state?
A: `(remaining, lo, hi)` — the expected continuation count plus an allowed range for the next byte, which relaxes to `(0x80, 0xBF)` after the first continuation. Counting alone accepts garbage; the shortest-form and range checks live in the first continuation byte.

---

Q: The UTF-8 first-continuation range table.
A: After `E0`: `A0..BF` (rejects overlong 3-byte). After `ED`: `80..9F` (rejects surrogates U+D800–DFFF). After `F0`: `90..BF` (rejects overlong 4-byte). After `F4`: `80..8F` (rejects > U+10FFFF). Others: `80..BF`. Also invalid outright: lead bytes `C0`, `C1` (all their forms overlong) and `F5..FF`.

---

Q: Why is `C0 80` rejected, and why does it matter?
A: Overlong NUL: it decodes to U+0000 under a sloppy decoder, sailing past `strlen`-based validators — the IIS unicode-traversal CVE class. Overlong rejection is a security requirement, not pedantry. Equivalent check: a 2/3/4-byte sequence must decode to $\ge$ U+0080 / U+0800 / U+10000.

---

Q: The HTTP chunked state machine.
A: SIZE_LINE → DATA → DATA_CRLF → SIZE_LINE … → 0-chunk → TRAILERS → DONE. Body is repeated hex-size (+ optional extensions) CRLF, then size bytes, then CRLF; terminated by a `0` chunk, optional trailer lines, and a final blank line. `4\r\nWiki\r\n5\r\npedia\r\n0\r\n\r\n` → `Wikipedia`.

---

Q: The four chunked-encoding bugs interviewers fish for.
A: CRLF torn across chunks (hold "expecting LF" as state); the post-data CRLF forgotten entirely (it belongs to no line); no length guard on the size line (a peer that never sends CRLF grows your buffer unboundedly); trailing data after DONE treated as ignorable — smuggling attacks live there. And the size is hex, attacker-controlled: same max-frame guard as length-prefix.

---

Q: Why is `self._buf = self._buf[n:]` per consume quadratic, and the fix?
A: Each slice copies the whole tail — consuming k items of size s from n bytes touches $O(n^2/s)$ bytes. Fix: cursor + periodic compaction — keep `pos`, and only `del self._buf[:pos]` when `pos > 4096 and pos * 2 > len(buf)`; one memmove, amortized O(1) per byte. Third option for huge frames: a deque of chunks + lazy join.

---

Q: The max-buffer guard?
A: Independent of declared lengths, cap `len(buf) - pos`. A decoder whose state can grow without bound under adversarial input is incorrect, same as an unchecked array write.

---

Q: Two streaming API contract details: empty chunks, and emitted payloads.
A: An empty chunk must be a no-op — not a crash, not a state reset. Emit copies (`bytes(view)`), never live views into an internal buffer that compaction will invalidate.

---

Q: The Python type-confusion trap in byte loops?
A: `for b in chunk` yields ints (the fast path); `chunk[i:i+1]` yields `bytes` — so `b == b"\x80"` against an int is silently always False, and every test fails at once.
